        Description copied from interface: XmlDataTreeCursor

Returns false if there are no more previous items and leaves the cursor unpositioned.

      • deleteObject

        public boolean deleteObject()
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Removes the tag-object-pair (single value or array of repeating values) from the current position. If there are tags following the current position, the cursor is positioned on the next tag and true is returned. If there is no next tag, the cursor is positioned on the previous tag and false is returned. If there are no remaining tags, the cursor is unpositioned and false is returned. This behavior is similar to legacy IDataCursor delete() behavior.
        Specified by:
        deleteObject in interface XmlDataCursor
        Returns:
        true if cursor is positioned on the next item after deletion

      • depth

        public int depth()
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataTreeCursor
        Return the stacked cursor depth. Initially zero. For every invocation of XmlDataTreeCursor.firstChild() or XmlDataTreeCursor.lastChild() that returns true, the depth increases by one. For every invocation of XmlDataTreeCursor.parent() that returns true, the depth decreases by one.
        Specified by:
        depth in interface XmlDataTreeCursor

      • firstPartial

        public boolean firstPartial(XmlDataContentTag key)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Position the cursor on the first partial-name occurrence of the specified content-tag and return true. Otherwise return false and leave the cursor unchanged. For purposes of comparison, the particle-ids of the tags are ignored during comparison in order to find the first occurrence regardless of its particle-id. It is as if the home() method is invoked and then the next() method is invoked until the condition tag.getPartialName().equals(cursor.getTag().getPartialName()) is satisfied.
        Specified by:
        firstPartial in interface XmlDataCursor

        Returns:

      • firstChild

        public boolean firstChild()
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataTreeCursor
        Positions this cursor on the first child of the current-value. Only group-values and complex-values with group-value content have children. If the current-value does not contain a child, (for example it contains a String or an empty IData), false is returned and the cursor position remains unchanged. If the current-value has one or more children, the current-cursor is pushed onto a stack and a new cursor is positioned on the first child item. If it is necessary to obtain a cursor on empty content, consider method XmlDataCursor.getValueCursor(int...).
        Specified by:
        firstChild in interface XmlDataTreeCursor
        Returns:
        true if the current-value has children

      • firstItem

        public boolean firstItem()
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataTreeCursor
        Positions this cursor on the first item. The first tag-object-pair becomes the current-object. If the first object is an array (repeating values), the cursor is positioned on first item in the array by setting the current-index to zero. In other words, the first item is the first member of a repeating values Object array. If the first object is not an array, then the first item is simply the first object.
        Specified by:

      • getObject

        public java.lang.Object getObject()
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Returns the current-object, the object stored at the current-position. If repeating values are present, then the entire array is returned. It is an error if the cursor is unpositioned. Normally, getObject will return a String, String[], IData, IData[], or Object[]. If the current-tag is an element-tag, a value or array of values is returned; if the the current-tag is a group-tag, a group-value or array of group-values is returned; if the current-tag is an any-tag, an any-item or array of any-items is returned; if the current-tag is a substitution-tag, a substitution-item or an array of substitution-items is returned.
        Specified by:
        getObject in interface XmlDataCursor
        Returns:
        object stored at current cursor position

      • setTag

        public void setTag(XmlDataContentTag tag)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Sets the tag of the current tag-object pair. The tag must be either an XmlDataElementTag, an XmlDataAnyTag, an XmlDataGroupTag, or an XmlDataSubstitutionTag. The tag must be compatible with the current value. A group tag can only be assigned to an item with IData content. An any tag can only be assigned to an item with content in the any format. An element tag may not be assigned to content that is in the any or substitution head format.
        Specified by:
        setTag in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        tag - is one of the XmlDataContentTags mentioned above.
